The Guilds of Aetheria
In a world of fractured kingdoms, endless border conflicts, and dangerous ruins, guilds have become essential institutions. They provide stability, expertise, and mutual protection where kings and lords often cannot. Most guilds are cross-racial but dominated by humans, with strong dwarven and gnomish influence in technical fields.
Here are the most important and influential guilds operating today:
1. The Azure Accord (Merchant & Trade Guild)
The largest and wealthiest guild in Aetheria.
Role: Controls major trade routes, caravans, and neutral free cities in the buffer zones.
Structure: Led by a Council of Master Traders (mostly humans, with halfling and gnome advisors).
Influence: Enormous economic power. They can sway kingdoms through loans, embargoes, or supply denial.
Notable Practices: Maintains “neutral ground” trading posts even near demonic borders. Heavily involved in the slave trade.
Symbol: A golden coin wrapped in blue ribbon.
2. The Veilwardens (Adventurers & Mercenary Guild)
The most famous guild for players and wandering heroes.
Role: Monster extermination, ruin and dungeon delving, escort missions, and mercenary contracts, herb collections, missing persons, special quests, labor request, bandit control, monster and minorraces (mostly goblins and ocs) population control.
Structure: Ranked from Copper, Iron, Bronze, Silver, Blood, Gold, Mythril, Obsidian, Adamant, Voidwalker. Local chapters in almost every major city and March. Small branches in small cities. Settlements only have a notice board, a local leader needs to approve quest acception for non-members.
Membership: Mostly humans and Beastkin, with occasional elves and dwarves.
Notable Practices: Issues bounties on demons, corrupted beasts, and bandit lords. Has a strict “no betrayal of contract” rule (violators are hunted).
Symbol: A cracked tower with a sword through it.
3. The Emberforge League (Artisan & Craftsmen Guild)
Heavily dwarven-led but open to all skilled crafters.
Role: Regulates master artisans, controls quality of weapons/armor, and protects trade secrets.
Structure: Run by Grandmasters in the major dwarven holds, with human and gnome branches.
Influence: Extremely powerful in military contracts. Only Emberforge-certified weapons are considered reliable by most armies.
Notable Practices: Harsh tests for mastery. Blacklisted crafters are effectively ruined.
Symbol: Hammer striking a glowing rune.
4. The Arcane Circle (Mage Guild)
The primary organization for trained mages.
Role: Regulates magical education, licenses spellcasters, and researches lost arts.
Structure: Divided into Colleges (Elemental, Nature, Spirit, etc.). Headed by an Archmagus elected every 20 years.
Membership: Mostly humans and elves. Very few dwarves.
Notable Practices: Strictly forbids Necromancy and most Void/Demon magic. Hunts rogue mages.
Symbol: A circle of twelve stars (representing the gods).
5. The Bloodfang Order (Monster & Demon Slayers)
Specialized hunter guild, popular among Beastkin and Marcher folk.
Role: Tracking and exterminating dangerous creatures, demonic incursions, and corrupted bloodlines.
Structure: Loose but highly respected. Chapters often double as local militias.
Notable Practices: Takes trophies (horns, scales, heads) as proof of kills. Offers high bounties on Greater Demons.
Symbol: A wolf’s skull pierced by a silver fang.
6. The Shadow Veil (Thieves, Assassins & Information Brokers)
The most secretive and feared guild.
Role: Espionage, assassination, smuggling, and information trading, theft, pickpoketing, heist.
Structure: Highly compartmentalized cells. Led by an unknown “Veilmaster.”
Membership: Mix of humans, tieflings, gnomes, and halflings.
Notable Practices: Operates under many front organizations (including some merchant houses). Has an ironclad “no killing of clients” policy.
Symbol: A hooded eye with a dagger beneath.
7. The Silver Thread (Bardic & Performers Guild)
Traveling entertainers, spies, and lore-keepers.
Role: Spread news, preserve (and twist) history, and provide morale during wars.
Structure: Loose troupes led by Master Bards.
Influence: Surprisingly powerful — a skilled bard can ruin a noble’s reputation across kingdoms.
Notable Practices: Many members secretly work for the Shadow Veil.
Symbol: A silver lyre with seven strings.
8. The Deep Delvers (Exploration & Ruin Recovery Guild)
Dwarven-heavy guild focused on underground and ancient ruins.
Role: Mapping lost holds, recovering Golden Age artifacts, and fighting underground threats.
Notable Practices: Works closely with the Emberforge League. Extremely dangerous — high mortality rate.
Symbol: A lantern inside a mountain.
General Guild Dynamics

Guild Neutrality: Most guilds claim political neutrality, but all have favorites among the fifteen human kingdoms.
Rivalries: The Arcane Circle clashes with independent mages. The Veilwardens and Bloodfang often compete for contracts. The Azure Accord is hated by many smaller guilds for monopolistic practices.
Membership Benefits: Protection, training, contracts, legal recognition, and access to guild halls/safe houses.
Dues & Rules: Usually 10–20% of earnings + strict codes of conduct. Expulsion is devastating. Higher the rank, higher the benefits.
Minor Race Influence: Gnomes dominate technical guilds, Halflings thrive in merchant and bardic circles.

Guilds are one of the few institutions that truly cross racial and national lines. In many ways, they are more stable and influential than most kings in this fractured age.
